<p>Choosing the right website audit tool depends on your specific needs, budget, and technical expertise. After testing every major audit tool across hundreds of sites, we have built this comparison to cut through the marketing and show you what each tool actually delivers.</p>

<p>This comparison covers the six most widely used audit tools: <a href="/website-audit-tools/ahrefs/">Ahrefs</a>, <a href="/website-audit-tools/semrush/">Semrush</a>, <a href="/website-audit-tools/screaming-frog/">Screaming Frog</a>, <a href="/website-audit-tools/moz/">Moz</a>, <a href="/website-audit-tools/se-ranking/">SE Ranking</a>, and <a href="/website-audit-tools/lighthouse/">Google Lighthouse</a>. Each excels in different scenarios, and the right choice for you may not be the most expensive or feature-rich option.</p>

<h2 id="comparison-criteria">Comparison Criteria</h2>

<p>We evaluated each tool across the criteria that matter most for practical website auditing. Here is what we compared and why each criterion matters.</p>

<p><strong>Issue coverage:</strong> The number and depth of technical SEO checks the tool performs. More is not always better since a tool that checks 170 things but presents results poorly is less useful than one that checks 120 things with clear prioritisation. We assessed both the quantity and the quality of issue detection.</p>

<p><strong>Crawl configuration:</strong> How much control you have over how the crawl runs. This includes crawl speed, URL inclusion/exclusion, JavaScript rendering, authentication, user agent selection, and robots.txt handling. Greater configuration flexibility means the tool can handle more complex crawling scenarios.</p>

<p><strong>Data export and API:</strong> The ability to export raw crawl data and access it programmatically. Technical SEOs often need to combine crawl data with data from other sources (analytics, rank tracking, CRM) for custom analysis. Tools with limited export options restrict this.</p>

<p><strong>Historical tracking:</strong> Whether the tool stores crawl results over time and provides comparison features. This is essential for ongoing monitoring and client reporting. Without historical data, every audit exists in isolation and you cannot demonstrate progress.</p>

<p><strong>Reporting:</strong> The quality, format, and customisability of reports. This includes white-label options for agencies, PDF export, and automated report scheduling.</p>

<p><strong>Ecosystem:</strong> What else the tool does beyond site auditing. Tools that are part of broader SEO platforms (like Ahrefs, Semrush, and Moz) offer the convenience of cross-referencing audit data with keywords, backlinks, and traffic data without switching tools.</p>

<p><strong>Price-to-value ratio:</strong> What you get relative to what you pay. An expensive tool that provides comprehensive features may be better value than a cheap tool that requires supplementary subscriptions to fill gaps.</p>

